An interface defines the shape of an object -- what fields it has and what types those fields are. Interfaces exist only at compile time and produce zero runtime code. They are the TypeScript equivalent of Python dataclasses or Pydantic models.

### Python Comparison

**Python (Pydantic):**
```python
class CollectionOut(BaseModel):
    id: int
    entity_type: str
    title: str
    description: str | None = None
    category_id: int
    is_active: bool
    is_archived: bool
    created_at: datetime
    updated_at: datetime
    items: list[CollectionItemOut] = []

    model_config = {"from_attributes": True}
```

**TypeScript:**
```typescript
export interface Collection {
    id: number;
    entity_type: string;
    title: string;
    description: string | null;
    category_id: number;
    is_active: boolean;
    is_archived: boolean;
    created_at: string;
    updated_at: string;
    items: CollectionItem[];
}
```

### Key Differences

- Interfaces produce zero runtime code -- there is no Collection class to instantiate
- Python Pydantic models validate data at runtime; TypeScript interfaces only check at compile time
- `datetime` becomes `string` because JSON serializes dates as ISO strings
- `list[CollectionItemOut]` becomes `CollectionItem[]` (array syntax)

